<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="695" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1127,219,850]" pageId="4" pageNumber="695">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,268,571,594]" pageId="4" pageNumber="695">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Distinguished from all other genera of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Barclay &amp; Sw" authorityYear="2015" box="[694,833,571,594]" class="Insecta" family="Ripiphoridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="695" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Ripiphoridae</taxonomicName>
by the following combination of characters: Antennae simple, symmetrical and unmodified. Elytra complete, simple, unmodified. Legs unmodified, all tibiae with two tibial spurs, tarsi with simple claws. Metatrochanter of characteristic shape, deeply indented at apex, heart-shaped (
<figureCitation box="[942,1066,667,690]" captionStart="Figs 10–15. 10–11" captionStartId="6.[151,188,1552,1571]" captionTargetBox="[193,1080,219,1521]" captionTargetId="figure-10@6.[174,1104,219,1534]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 10–15. 10–11 – detail of heart-shaped, deeply indented metatrochanter (10 – I. paradoxus sp. nov., paratype; 11 – I. monneorum sp. nov., holotype). 12–15 – detail of head, frontal view: (12 – I. paradoxus sp. nov., paratype; 13 – I. youngi sp. nov., holotype; 14 – I. cechorum sp. nov., paratype; 15 – I. monneorum sp. nov., paratype). Scale bars = 1 mm. Images by Harry Taylor (Natural History Museum, London)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5303725" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5303725/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="695">Figs 10–11</figureCitation>
). The shape of the metatrochanter is apparently apomorphic for this taxon.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="695" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1127,219,850]" pageId="4" pageNumber="695">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,279,731,754]" pageId="4" pageNumber="695">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name is derived from the suffix - 
<emphasis box="[665,760,731,754]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="695">rhipidius</emphasis>
, taken from the name of the similar 
<taxonomicName authority="Iablokoff-Khnzorian, 1986" authorityName="Iablokoff-Khnzorian" authorityYear="1986" box="[151,573,763,786]" class="Insecta" family="Ripiphoridae" genus="Eorhipidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="695" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,276,763,786]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="695">Eorhipidius</emphasis>
Iablokoff-Khnzorian, 1986
</taxonomicName>
(now a synonym of 
<taxonomicName authority="Reitter, 1895" authorityName="Reitter" authorityYear="1895" box="[803,1068,763,786]" class="Insecta" family="Coleoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Pterydrias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="695" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[803,916,763,786]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="695">Pterydrias</emphasis>
Reitter, 1895
</taxonomicName>
), and the name Ivie in honour of Michael and Ladonna Ivie of Bozeman, 
<collectingRegion box="[876,974,795,818]" country="United States of America" name="Montana" pageId="4" pageNumber="695">Montana</collectingRegion>
, for their kind hospitality and expert and persistent encouragement. The genus name is masculine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
